{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506673"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2555"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2555"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.53,0.25,0.15,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50479"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2555"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35696"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"255"},{"type":"tags","id":"5605"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3667"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50479"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEndotracheal intubation is about to be performed on a patient who is being prepared for an elective procedure on part of a general surgical list. The induction agents have been given and a video laryngoscope is used to insert and place the endotracheal tube. The next step is to ensure that the tube is in the correct location.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would most appropriately confirm that endotracheal intubation was successful?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Limited chest wall movement on the left side","Hearing equal breath sounds at both axillae","A flat end tidal CO2 trace","A chest X-ray to visualise the position","An oxygen saturation of 100%"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGenerally after intubation there are three important markers that endotracheal intubation has occurred to allow effective ventilation of the patient. These are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWaveform capnography of the end tidal CO2 (gold-standard for confirming correct ETT placement)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEqual air entry on auscultation of both lungs (at the axilla)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFogging of the tube\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHearing equal breath sounds at both axillae\u003C/strong\u003E suggests correct placement of the tube. This is an important sign to check by auscultation immediately after a patient has been intubated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eend tidal CO2 reading\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E(via waveform capnography) \u003C/strong\u003Eis crucial in ensuring the tube is placed in the correctly and ventilation is effective. A normal end tidal CO2 that would be expected if the tube was effectively ventilating the lungs is 30-45mmHg. Whilst waveform capnography is considered the gold standard for confirming endotracheal intubation, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eflat trace\u003C/strong\u003E (the option given in this scenario) suggests the tube is misplaced and therefore is incorrect. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFogging of the tube can also be used alongside these other clinical signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnequal or \u003Cstrong\u003Elimited chest wall movement\u003C/strong\u003E suggests that the tube may have gone down one of the main bronchus and hence is only ventilating one lung effectively. This should be checked by auscultating the lungs for equal air entry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen saturation\u003C/strong\u003E is a delayed and unreliable marker of ventilation. The SpO2 can take up to 5 minutes to decline when a patient has been appropriately pre-oxygenated prior to an elective induction, so it should not be relied upon for confirming tube placement and adequate oxygenation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E can confirm the position of a tube, but is not required in an elective list where the above three methods can be used clinically to confirm the tube placement. It would hold up the surgical list and expose the patient to unnecessary radiation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Capnography (end tidal CO2 trace) is an important and reliable measure of correct endotracheal tube placement","Chest x-ray and SpO2 are not reliable measures of confirming correct endotracheal tube placement and successful intubation","After intubation it is important to confirm the placement of the tube by auscultating breath sounds in both axilla"],"references":["Nickson, C, 2020. Capnography. Life in the Fastlane. Access at: https://litfl.com/capnography-waveform-interpretation/.","American College of Emergency Physicians, 2016. Verification of Endotracheal Tube Placement. Access at: https://www.acep.org/patient-care/policy-statements/verification-of-endotracheal-tube-placement/.","Grmec S. Comparison of three different methods to confirm tracheal tube placement in emergency intubation. Intensive Care Med. 2002 Jun;28(6):701-4. doi: 10.1007/s00134-002-1290-x. Epub 2002 Apr 30. PMID: 12107674."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35696"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2555"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanation